<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the CBI Submission</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">OAR0009</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the CBI Submission</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CBI welcomes the opportunity to respond to the Education Select Committee’s inquiry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ofsted’s Annual Report on Education 2012-2013. As the UK’s leading business organisation, speaking for some 240,000 businesses that together employ around a third of the private sector workforce, the CBI recognises that improvements in the education system are a top priority. With offices in Brussels, Washington, Beijing and Delhi to communicate the British business voice globally as well as across the UK, the CBI is intensely aware of rising educational standards elsewhere in the world and the pressing need for school systems in all parts of the UK to raise their overall levels of attainment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CBI believes improving our education and skills system is the most important long-term investment the UK can make to enhance economic growth and social inclusion. We therefore welcome the consistent emphasis on improving standards in schools and building confidence in the quality of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> inspectorate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In November 2012, the CBI published </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">First </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Steps, the outcome of a major review of our school systems. The report from the review set out businesses’ views on the importance of increasing rigour and ambition, and called for reform of the schools system. In this response, we draw on the substantial body of work and wider research, setting out the view that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We need a clear statement of what it is we are asking schools to deliver. This should then form the basis of how schools are judged and held accountable by Ofsted.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Strong leadership and governance are key to ensuring successful education outcomes for young people, and Ofsted should continue to focus more acutely on these aspects of schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">’ performance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This response focuses on the importance of leadership and governance in schools as a key driver of standards and outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and how to improve these aspects of education. Much of this draws on a recent CBI report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Leading the Way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, published in November 2013.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">We need a clear statement of what it is we are asking schools to deliver. This should then form the basis of how schools are judged and held accountable by Ofsted.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The best education systems globally, and the best schools within the UK, start with a clear idea of what they should deliver, aligning all activities within the school to meeting this goal. The accountability system we have in this country</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, however, has created perverse incentives for schools and teachers to focus on a narrow set of metrics as opposed to supporting the holistic development of every child – a move away from league tables towards greater use of narrative reports would support the change we need.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A successful outcome for schools is much more than just exam results, and the way that schools are judged should reflect this. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The new progress measures for exam performance will ensure a focus on every child but only a shift to more narrative reporting by Ofsted on other areas of school performance can deliver real change, so that heads are held to account on both academic performance and the school’s wider eco-system. The effect of this, in time, will be to shift the focus of the accountability system to understanding the entire DNA of a school – not just its exam results.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Strong leadership and governance are key to ensuring successful education outcomes for young people, and Ofsted should continue to focus more acut</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ely on this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Strong leadership and governance are integral to creating the schools that we want. Improvement in standards is driven from the top, with the evidence showing more effective governance and high quality leadership and management together have a positive effect on the quality of provision, and consequently on pupil achievement</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he ann</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ual report from Ofsted highlights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that 18% of schools have lea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dership that is judged to be less than good, with low aspirations for their school and its pupils, and a lack of challenge from governors</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We know the negative impact that poor leadership and governance can have on the quality of the education young people receive, so this needs to be tackled. There must therefore be a clear push to raise the standards of leadership to match the best performing schools, and then a push to improve standards further across the board. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We welcome the steps taken by the government to increase the autonomy of schools, giving headteachers the freedom to lead and manage as senior professionals, but the increase in responsibilities for school leaders requires a support structure to ensure effectiveness. This structure should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">involve greater cooperation between schools, clearer expectations of leaders, an increased focus on professional development, and – vitally – more effective governing bodies.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A skilled and competent governing body that defines clearly the strategic aims for the school and holds the headteacher to account for delivery is needed to drive the positive change we need in schools. But, as the annual report from Ofsted recognises, too many are not performing this role to a high enough standard</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This is particularly concerning given the increasing levels of freedoms within the school system and the expanded challenges schools now face. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A professionalisation of school governance is needed across the board to improve standards and effectiveness. This involves not only learning from the business experience of corporate governance – for example around board composition, rigour in holding to account, and in succession planning, but also in ensuring a continual focus on the strategic role governing bodies have to play. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In line with this, there is real value in attracting more people from industry to serve as school governors. This should involve a concerted effort to raise the profile of governance and encourage volunteering from the government, from the education sector, and from businesses themselves.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Accountability drives behaviour in schools, so we must ensure that the frameworks in place encourage the behaviour we want. Whilst we welcome the moves from Ofsted to assess how well school leadership promotes improved teaching, and at how effectively governors hold senior leaders to account, a sharper and more prominent focus on these crucial drivers of standards in schools would ensure quality leadership and governance becomes a real priority.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Leading the way: improving school governance and leadership</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, CBI, November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">The Annual Report of Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector of Education, Children’s Services and Skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, Ofsted, December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Ibid.</span></p></body></html>